<subSubSection id="FF9D65303418FF9CFF5CC73A1E329048" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" type="description">
<paragraph id="B73836BB3418FF9CFF5CC73A1E329048" blockId="3.[178,1085,519,600]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
C o m m e n t: The above female most likely represents an undescribed species. It is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="70874D383418FF9CFEB0C7171B9A902A" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2011" box="[350,434,549,570]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Aleochara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rosei">
<emphasis id="85F3EAA93418FF9CFEB0C7171B9A902A" box="[350,434,549,570]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">A. rosei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but distinguished by larger body size, slightly less slender antennae, a more transverse pronotum, and a spermatheca of different shape (
<figureCitation id="2FBC2A3E3418FF9CFC2CC7701E259048" box="[962,1037,578,600]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[178,1072,212,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-1@7.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9-16: Liogluta nigrobusta nov.sp. (9-11), Vulda substricta nov.sp. (12-15), and Aleochara sp. (16): (9) female tergite VIII; (10) female sternite VIII; (11, 16) spermatheca; (12) forebody; (13) head; (14) antenna; (15) aedeagus. Scale bars: 12-14: 1.0 mm; 9-10, 15: 0.5 mm; 11, 16: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416233/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
